#let title = [The Map is not the Territory]

#let body = [

#quote(block: true)[
_
The system has been malignantly growing for years... built by hands and minds that have long since moved on.
By chance, a skilled developer joins your project
--- exactly who you needed.
They seem eager to help; they've used these technologies before.
There's just one problem... Your documentation is months out of date and incomplete.
Without a map --- what should have been a quick handoff becomes a month-long archeology project.
Before you know it, deadlines start to slip...
_
]

Every engineering organization runs on maps --- slide decks, diagrams, wikis, tribal knowledge --- the accumulated record of what the system is and how it works. 
But maps are not the code. They are maintained by hand, updated when someone remembers, and abandoned when priorities shift. As the system evolves, the maps fall behind.

#quote(block: true, attribution: [@evans2003])[
  External documents and diagrams do not affect the behavior of the program, so they fall out of sync.
]

#quote(block: true, attribution: [@korzybski1933[p. 750 (Supplement III)]])[
  ...such a map would be misguiding, wasteful of effort,. In case of emergencies, it might be seriously harmful,.
]

Stakeholders reading these maps believe they understand the risk of new work, the cost to deliver, the cost to maintain. They are making real decisions from faulty maps --- and the territory does not forgive the error.

]
